[src:python/asyncio-task] This section outlines high-level asyncio APIs to work with coroutines and Tasks.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Coroutines declared with the async/await syntax is the preferred way of writing asyncio applications.
[src:python/asyncio-task] We say that an object is an **awaitable** object if it can be used in an `await` expression.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Many asyncio APIs are designed to accept awaitables.
[src:python/asyncio-task] There are three main types of *awaitable* objects: **coroutines**, **Tasks**, and **Futures**.
[src:python/asyncio-task] A `Future` is a special **low-level** awaitable object that represents an **eventual result** of an asynchronous operation.
[src:python/asyncio-task] When a Future object is *awaited* it means that the coroutine will wait until the Future is resolved in some other place.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Future objects in asyncio are needed to allow callback-based code to be used with async/await.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Normally **there is no need** to create Future objects at the application level code.
[src:python/asyncio-task] A good example of a low-level function that returns a Future object is `loop.run_in_executor()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Wrap the *coro* coroutine into a `Task` and schedule its execution.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The full function signature is largely the same as that of the `Task` constructor (or factory) - all of the keyword arguments to this function are passed through to that interface.
[src:python/asyncio-task] An optional keyword-only *context* argument allows specifying a custom `contextvars.Context` for the *coro* to run in.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The current context copy is created when no *context* is provided.
[src:python/asyncio-task] An optional keyword-only *eager_start* argument allows specifying if the task should execute eagerly during the call to create_task, or be scheduled later.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If *eager_start* is not passed the mode set by `loop.set_task_factory()` will be used.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The task is executed in the loop returned by `get_running_loop()`, `RuntimeError` is raised if there is no running loop in current thread.
[src:python/asyncio-task] `asyncio.TaskGroup.create_task()` is a new alternative leveraging structural concurrency; it allows for waiting for a group of related tasks with strong safety guarantees.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Save a reference to the result of this function, to avoid a task disappearing mid-execution.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The event loop only keeps weak references to tasks.
[src:python/asyncio-task] A task that isn’t referenced elsewhere may get garbage collected at any time, even before it’s done.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.8: Added the *name* parameter.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.11: Added the *context* parameter.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.14: Added the *eager_start* parameter by passing on all *kwargs*.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Tasks can easily and safely be cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] When a task is cancelled, `asyncio.CancelledError` will be raised in the task at the next opportunity.
[src:python/asyncio-task] It is recommended that coroutines use `try/finally` blocks to robustly perform clean-up logic.
[src:python/asyncio-task] In case `asyncio.CancelledError` is explicitly caught, it should generally be propagated when clean-up is complete.
[src:python/asyncio-task] `asyncio.CancelledError` directly subclasses `BaseException` so most code will not need to be aware of it.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The asyncio components that enable structured concurrency, like `asyncio.TaskGroup` and `asyncio.timeout()`, are implemented using cancellation internally and might misbehave if a coroutine swallows `asyncio.CancelledError`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Similarly, user code should not generally call `uncancel`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] However, in cases when suppressing `asyncio.CancelledError` is truly desired, it is necessary to also call `uncancel()` to completely remove the cancellation state.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Task groups combine a task creation API with a convenient and reliable way to wait for all tasks in the group to finish.
[src:python/asyncio-task] An asynchronous context manager holding a group of tasks.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Tasks can be added to the group using `create_task()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] All tasks are awaited when the context manager exits.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The signature matches that of `asyncio.create_task()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If the task group is inactive (e.g. not yet entered, already finished, or in the process of shutting down), we will close the given `coro`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.13: Close the given coroutine if the task group is not active.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The `async with` statement will wait for all tasks in the group to finish.
[src:python/asyncio-task] While waiting, new tasks may still be added to the group (for example, by passing `tg` into one of the coroutines and calling `tg.create_task()` in that coroutine).
[src:python/asyncio-task] Once the last task has finished and the `async with` block is exited, no new tasks may be added to the group.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The first time any of the tasks belonging to the group fails with an exception other than `asyncio.CancelledError`, the remaining tasks in the group are cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] No further tasks can then be added to the group.
[src:python/asyncio-task] At this point, if the body of the `async with` statement is still active (i.e., `__aexit__()` hasn’t been called yet), the task directly containing the `async with` statement is also cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The resulting `asyncio.CancelledError` will interrupt an `await`, but it will not bubble out of the containing `async with` statement.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Once all tasks have finished, if any tasks have failed with an exception other than `asyncio.CancelledError`, those exceptions are combined in an `ExceptionGroup` or `BaseExceptionGroup` (as appropriate; see their documentation) which is then raised.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Two base exceptions are treated specially: If any task fails with `KeyboardInterrupt` or `SystemExit`, the task group still cancels the remaining tasks and waits for them, but then the initial `KeyboardInterrupt` or `SystemExit` is re-raised instead of `ExceptionGroup` or `BaseExceptionGroup`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The exception passed into `__aexit__()`, unless it is `asyncio.CancelledError`, is also included in the exception group.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The same special case is made for `KeyboardInterrupt` and `SystemExit` as in the previous paragraph.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Task groups are careful not to mix up the internal cancellation used to “wake up” their `__aexit__()` with cancellation requests for the task in which they are running made by other parties.
[src:python/asyncio-task] In particular, when one task group is syntactically nested in another, and both experience an exception in one of their child tasks simultaneously, the inner task group will process its exceptions, and then the outer task group will receive another cancellation and process its own exceptions.
[src:python/asyncio-task] In the case where a task group is cancelled externally and also must raise an `ExceptionGroup`, it will call the parent task’s `cancel()` method.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This ensures that a `asyncio.CancelledError` will be raised at the next `await`, so the cancellation is not lost.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Task groups preserve the cancellation count reported by `asyncio.Task.cancelling()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.13: Improved handling of simultaneous internal and external cancellations and correct preservation of cancellation counts.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If *result* is provided, it is returned to the caller when the coroutine completes.
[src:python/asyncio-task] `sleep()` always suspends the current task, allowing other tasks to run.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Setting the delay to 0 provides an optimized path to allow other tasks to run.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This can be used by long-running functions to avoid blocking the event loop for the full duration of the function call.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.10: Removed the *loop* parameter.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.13: Raises `ValueError` if *delay* is `nan`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Run awaitable objects in the *aws* sequence *concurrently*.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If any awaitable in *aws* is a coroutine, it is automatically scheduled as a Task.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If all awaitables are completed successfully, the result is an aggregate list of returned values.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The order of result values corresponds to the order of awaitables in *aws*.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If *return_exceptions* is `False` (default), the first raised exception is immediately propagated to the task that awaits on `gather()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Other awaitables in the *aws* sequence **won’t be cancelled** and will continue to run.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If *return_exceptions* is `True`, exceptions are treated the same as successful results, and aggregated in the result list.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If `gather()` is *cancelled*, all submitted awaitables (that have not completed yet) are also *cancelled*.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If any Task or Future from the *aws* sequence is *cancelled*, it is treated as if it raised `CancelledError` – the `gather()` call is **not** cancelled in this case.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This is to prevent the cancellation of one submitted Task/Future to cause other Tasks/Futures to be cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] A new alternative to create and run tasks concurrently and wait for their completion is `asyncio.TaskGroup`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] *TaskGroup* provides stronger safety guarantees than *gather* for scheduling a nesting of subtasks: if a task (or a subtask, a task scheduled by a task) raises an exception, *TaskGroup* will, while *gather* will not, cancel the remaining scheduled tasks.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If *return_exceptions* is false, cancelling gather() after it has been marked done won’t cancel any submitted awaitables.
[src:python/asyncio-task] For instance, gather can be marked done after propagating an exception to the caller, therefore, calling `gather.cancel()` after catching an exception (raised by one of the awaitables) from gather won’t cancel any other awaitables.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.7: If the *gather* itself is cancelled, the cancellation is propagated regardless of *return_exceptions*.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Deprecated since version 3.10: Deprecation warning is emitted if no positional arguments are provided or not all positional arguments are Future-like objects and there is no running event loop.
[src:python/asyncio-task] A task factory for eager task execution.
[src:python/asyncio-task] When using this factory (via `loop.set_task_factory(asyncio.eager_task_factory)`), coroutines begin execution synchronously during `Task` construction.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Tasks are only scheduled on the event loop if they block.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This can be a performance improvement as the overhead of loop scheduling is avoided for coroutines that complete synchronously.
[src:python/asyncio-task] A common example where this is beneficial is coroutines which employ caching or memoization to avoid actual I/O when possible.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Immediate execution of the coroutine is a semantic change.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If the coroutine returns or raises, the task is never scheduled to the event loop.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If the coroutine execution blocks, the task is scheduled to the event loop.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This change may introduce behavior changes to existing applications.
[src:python/asyncio-task] For example, the application’s task execution order is likely to change.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Create an eager task factory, similar to `eager_task_factory()`, using the provided *custom_task_constructor* when creating a new task instead of the default `Task`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This function returns a *callable* intended to be used as a task factory of an event loop via `loop.set_task_factory(factory)`).
[src:python/asyncio-task] Protect an awaitable object from being `cancelled`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If *aw* is a coroutine it is automatically scheduled as a Task.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If `something()` is cancelled by other means (i.e. from within itself) that would also cancel `shield()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Save a reference to tasks passed to this function, to avoid a task disappearing mid-execution.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Deprecated since version 3.10: Deprecation warning is emitted if *aw* is not Future-like object and there is no running event loop.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Return an asynchronous context manager that can be used to limit the amount of time spent waiting on something.
[src:python/asyncio-task] In either case, the context manager can be rescheduled after creation using `Timeout.reschedule()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If `long_running_task` takes more than 10 seconds to complete, the context manager will cancel the current task and handle the resulting `asyncio.CancelledError` internally, transforming it into a `TimeoutError` which can be caught and handled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The `asyncio.timeout()` context manager is what transforms the `asyncio.CancelledError` into a `TimeoutError`, which means the `TimeoutError` can only be caught *outside* of the context manager.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The context manager produced by `asyncio.timeout()` can be rescheduled to a different deadline and inspected.
[src:python/asyncio-task] An asynchronous context manager for cancelling overdue coroutines.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Prefer using `asyncio.timeout()` or `asyncio.timeout_at()` rather than instantiating `Timeout` directly.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Timeout context managers can be safely nested.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Similar to `asyncio.timeout()`, except *when* is the absolute time to stop waiting, or `None`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Wait for the *aw* awaitable to complete with a timeout.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If a timeout occurs, it cancels the task and raises `TimeoutError`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] To avoid the task `cancellation`, wrap it in `shield()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The function will wait until the future is actually cancelled, so the total wait time may exceed the *timeout*.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If an exception happens during cancellation, it is propagated.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If the wait is cancelled, the future *aw* is also cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.7: When *aw* is cancelled due to a timeout, `wait_for` waits for *aw* to be cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Previously, it raised `TimeoutError` immediately.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.11: Raises `TimeoutError` instead of `asyncio.TimeoutError`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Run `Future` and `Task` instances in the *aws* iterable concurrently and block until the condition specified by *return_when*.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Returns two sets of Tasks/Futures: `(done, pending)`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Note that this function does not raise `TimeoutError`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Futures or Tasks that aren’t done when the timeout occurs are simply returned in the second set.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Unlike `wait_for()`, `wait()` does not cancel the futures when a timeout occurs.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.11: Passing coroutine objects to `wait()` directly is forbidden.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.12: Added support for generators yielding tasks.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Run awaitable objects in the *aws* iterable concurrently.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The returned object can be iterated to obtain the results of the awaitables as they finish.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The object returned by `as_completed()` can be iterated as an asynchronous iterator or a plain iterator.
[src:python/asyncio-task] When asynchronous iteration is used, the originally-supplied awaitables are yielded if they are tasks or futures.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This makes it easy to correlate previously-scheduled tasks with their results.
[src:python/asyncio-task] During asynchronous iteration, implicitly-created tasks will be yielded for supplied awaitables that aren’t tasks or futures.
[src:python/asyncio-task] When used as a plain iterator, each iteration yields a new coroutine that returns the result or raises the exception of the next completed awaitable.
[src:python/asyncio-task] A `TimeoutError` is raised if the timeout occurs before all awaitables are done.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This is raised by the `async for` loop during asynchronous iteration or by the coroutines yielded during plain iteration.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Deprecated since version 3.10: Deprecation warning is emitted if not all awaitable objects in the *aws* iterable are Future-like objects and there is no running event loop.
