[src:python/asyncio-task] A `Future-like` object that runs a Python coroutine.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Tasks are used to run coroutines in event loops.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If a coroutine awaits on a Future, the Task suspends the execution of the coroutine and waits for the completion of the Future.
[src:python/asyncio-task] When the Future is *done*, the execution of the wrapped coroutine resumes.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Event loops use cooperative scheduling: an event loop runs one Task at a time.
[src:python/asyncio-task] While a Task awaits for the completion of a Future, the event loop runs other Tasks, callbacks, or performs IO operations.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Use the high-level `asyncio.create_task()` function to create Tasks, or the low-level `loop.create_task()` or `ensure_future()` functions.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Manual instantiation of Tasks is discouraged.
[src:python/asyncio-task] To cancel a running Task use the `cancel()` method.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Calling it will cause the Task to throw a `CancelledError` exception into the wrapped coroutine.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If a coroutine is awaiting on a Future object during cancellation, the Future object will be cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] `cancelled()` can be used to check if the Task was cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The method returns `True` if the wrapped coroutine did not suppress the `CancelledError` exception and was actually cancelled.
[src:python/asyncio-task] `asyncio.Task` inherits from `Future` all of its APIs except `Future.set_result()` and `Future.set_exception()`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If no *context* is provided, the Task copies the current context and later runs its coroutine in the copied context.
[src:python/asyncio-task] An optional keyword-only *eager_start* argument allows eagerly starting the execution of the `asyncio.Task` at task creation time.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If set to `True` and the event loop is running, the task will start executing the coroutine immediately, until the first time the coroutine blocks.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If the coroutine returns or raises without blocking, the task will be finished eagerly and will skip scheduling to the event loop.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Tasks are generic over the return type of their wrapped coroutines.
