[src:python/asyncio-task] If the Task is already *done* or *cancelled*, return `False`, otherwise, return `True`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The method arranges for a `CancelledError` exception to be thrown into the wrapped coroutine on the next cycle of the event loop.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The coroutine then has a chance to clean up or even deny the request by suppressing the exception with a `try` … … `except CancelledError` … `finally` block.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Therefore, unlike `Future.cancel()`, `Task.cancel()` does not guarantee that the Task will be cancelled, although suppressing cancellation completely is not common and is actively discouraged.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Should the coroutine nevertheless decide to suppress the cancellation, it needs to call `Task.uncancel()` in addition to catching the exception.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.9: Added the *msg* parameter.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.11: The `msg` parameter is propagated from cancelled task to its awaiter.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Return `True` if the Task is *cancelled*.
[src:python/asyncio-task] The Task is *cancelled* when the cancellation was requested with `cancel()` and the wrapped coroutine propagated the `CancelledError` exception thrown into it.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Decrement the count of cancellation requests to this Task.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Returns the remaining number of cancellation requests.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Note that once execution of a cancelled task completed, further calls to `uncancel()` are ineffective.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This method is used by asyncio’s internals and isn’t expected to be used by end-user code.
[src:python/asyncio-task] In particular, if a Task gets successfully uncancelled, this allows for elements of structured concurrency like Task groups and `asyncio.timeout()` to continue running, isolating cancellation to the respective structured block.
[src:python/asyncio-task] While the block with `make_request()` and `make_another_request()` might get cancelled due to the timeout, `unrelated_code()` should continue running even in case of the timeout.
[src:python/asyncio-task] `TaskGroup` context managers use `uncancel()` in a similar fashion.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If end-user code is, for some reason, suppressing cancellation by catching `CancelledError`, it needs to call this method to remove the cancellation state.
[src:python/asyncio-task] When this method decrements the cancellation count to zero, the method checks if a previous `cancel()` call had arranged for `CancelledError` to be thrown into the task.
[src:python/asyncio-task] If it hasn’t been thrown yet, that arrangement will be rescinded (by resetting the internal `_must_cancel` flag).
[src:python/asyncio-task] Changed in version 3.13: Changed to rescind pending cancellation requests upon reaching zero.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Return the number of pending cancellation requests to this Task, i.e., the number of calls to `cancel()` less the number of `uncancel()` calls.
[src:python/asyncio-task] Note that if this number is greater than zero but the Task is still executing, `cancelled()` will still return `False`.
[src:python/asyncio-task] This is because this number can be lowered by calling `uncancel()`, which can lead to the task not being cancelled after all if the cancellation requests go down to zero.
[src:python/classes] Classes provide a means of bundling data and functionality together.
[src:python/classes] Creating a new class creates a new *type* of object, allowing new *instances* of that type to be made.
[src:python/classes] Each class instance can have attributes attached to it for maintaining its state.
[src:python/classes] Class instances can also have methods (defined by its class) for modifying its state.
[src:python/classes] Compared with other programming languages, Python’s class mechanism adds classes with a minimum of new syntax and semantics.
[src:python/classes] It is a mixture of the class mechanisms found in C++ and Modula-3.
[src:python/classes] Python classes provide all the standard features of Object Oriented Programming: the class inheritance mechanism allows multiple base classes, a derived class can override any methods of its base class or classes, and a method can call the method of a base class with the same name.
[src:python/classes] Objects can contain arbitrary amounts and kinds of data.
[src:python/classes] As is true for modules, classes partake of the dynamic nature of Python: they are created at runtime, and can be modified further after creation.
[src:python/classes] In C++ terminology, normally class members (including the data members) are *public* (except see below Private Variables), and all member functions are *virtual*.
[src:python/classes] As in Modula-3, there are no shorthands for referencing the object’s members from its methods: the method function is declared with an explicit first argument representing the object, which is provided implicitly by the call.
[src:python/classes] As in Smalltalk, classes themselves are objects.
[src:python/classes] This provides semantics for importing and renaming.
[src:python/classes] Unlike C++ and Modula-3, built-in types can be used as base classes for extension by the user.
[src:python/classes] Also, like in C++, most built-in operators with special syntax (arithmetic operators, subscripting etc.) can be redefined for class instances.
[src:python/classes] (Lacking universally accepted terminology to talk about classes, I will make occasional use of Smalltalk and C++ terms.
[src:python/classes] Objects have individuality, and multiple names (in multiple scopes) can be bound to the same object.
[src:python/classes] This is known as aliasing in other languages.
[src:python/classes] This is usually not appreciated on a first glance at Python, and can be safely ignored when dealing with immutable basic types (numbers, strings, tuples).
[src:python/classes] However, aliasing has a possibly surprising effect on the semantics of Python code involving mutable objects such as lists, dictionaries, and most other types.
[src:python/classes] This is usually used to the benefit of the program, since aliases behave like pointers in some respects.
[src:python/classes] For example, passing an object is cheap since only a pointer is passed by the implementation; and if a function modifies an object passed as an argument, the caller will see the change — this eliminates the need for two different argument passing mechanisms as in Pascal.
[src:python/classes] Before introducing classes, I first have to tell you something about Python’s scope rules.
[src:python/classes] Class definitions play some neat tricks with namespaces, and you need to know how scopes and namespaces work to fully understand what’s going on.
[src:python/classes] Incidentally, knowledge about this subject is useful for any advanced Python programmer.
[src:python/classes] A *namespace* is a mapping from names to objects.
[src:python/classes] Most namespaces are currently implemented as Python dictionaries, but that’s normally not noticeable in any way (except for performance), and it may change in the future.
[src:python/classes] Examples of namespaces are: the set of built-in names (containing functions such as `abs()`, and built-in exception names); the global names in a module; and the local names in a function invocation.
[src:python/classes] In a sense the set of attributes of an object also form a namespace.
[src:python/classes] The important thing to know about namespaces is that there is absolutely no relation between names in different namespaces; for instance, two different modules may both define a function `maximize` without confusion — users of the modules must prefix it with the module name.
[src:python/classes] By the way, I use the word *attribute* for any name following a dot — for example, in the expression `z.real`, `real` is an attribute of the object `z`.
[src:python/classes] Strictly speaking, references to names in modules are attribute references: in the expression `modname.funcname`, `modname` is a module object and `funcname` is an attribute of it.
[src:python/classes] Attributes may be read-only or writable.
[src:python/classes] In the latter case, assignment to attributes is possible.
[src:python/classes] Module attributes are writable: you can write `modname.the_answer = 42`.
[src:python/classes] Writable attributes may also be deleted with the `del` statement.
[src:python/classes] For example, `del modname.the_answer` will remove the attribute `the_answer` from the object named by `modname`.
[src:python/classes] Namespaces are created at different moments and have different lifetimes.
[src:python/classes] The namespace containing the built-in names is created when the Python interpreter starts up, and is never deleted.
[src:python/classes] The global namespace for a module is created when the module definition is read in; normally, module namespaces also last until the interpreter quits.
[src:python/classes] The statements executed by the top-level invocation of the interpreter, either read from a script file or interactively, are considered part of a module called `__main__`, so they have their own global namespace.
[src:python/classes] The local namespace for a function is created when the function is called, and deleted when the function returns or raises an exception that is not handled within the function.
[src:python/classes] (Actually, forgetting would be a better way to describe what actually happens.) Of course, recursive invocations each have their own local namespace.
[src:python/classes] A *scope* is a textual region of a Python program where a namespace is directly accessible. “Directly accessible” here means that an unqualified reference to a name attempts to find the name in the namespace.
[src:python/classes] Although scopes are determined statically, they are used dynamically.
[src:python/classes] If a name is declared global, then all references and assignments go directly to the next-to-last scope containing the module’s global names.
[src:python/classes] Usually, the local scope references the local names of the (textually) current function.
[src:python/classes] Outside functions, the local scope references the same namespace as the global scope: the module’s namespace.
[src:python/classes] Class definitions place yet another namespace in the local scope.
[src:python/classes] It is important to realize that scopes are determined textually: the global scope of a function defined in a module is that module’s namespace, no matter from where or by what alias the function is called.
[src:python/classes] On the other hand, the actual search for names is done dynamically, at run time — however, the language definition is evolving towards static name resolution, at “compile” time, so don’t rely on dynamic name resolution!
[src:python/classes] A special quirk of Python is that – if no `global` or `nonlocal` statement is in effect – assignments to names always go into the innermost scope.
[src:python/classes] Assignments do not copy data — they just bind names to objects.
[src:python/classes] The same is true for deletions: the statement `del x` removes the binding of `x` from the namespace referenced by the local scope.
[src:python/classes] In fact, all operations that introduce new names use the local scope: in particular, `import` statements and function definitions bind the module or function name in the local scope.
[src:python/classes] The `global` statement can be used to indicate that particular variables live in the global scope and should be rebound there; the `nonlocal` statement indicates that particular variables live in an enclosing scope and should be rebound there.
[src:python/classes] Note how the *local* assignment (which is default) didn’t change *scope_test*'s binding of *spam*.
[src:python/classes] The `nonlocal` assignment changed *scope_test*'s binding of *spam*, and the `global` assignment changed the module-level binding.
[src:python/classes] You can also see that there was no previous binding for *spam* before the `global` assignment.
[src:python/classes] Classes introduce a little bit of new syntax, three new object types, and some new semantics.
[src:python/classes] Class definitions, like function definitions (`def` statements) must be executed before they have any effect.
[src:python/classes] In practice, the statements inside a class definition will usually be function definitions, but other statements are allowed, and sometimes useful — we’ll come back to this later.
[src:python/classes] The function definitions inside a class normally have a peculiar form of argument list, dictated by the calling conventions for methods — again, this is explained later.
[src:python/classes] When a class definition is entered, a new namespace is created, and used as the local scope — thus, all assignments to local variables go into this new namespace.
[src:python/classes] In particular, function definitions bind the name of the new function here.
[src:python/classes] When a class definition is left normally (via the end), a *class object* is created.
[src:python/classes] This is basically a wrapper around the contents of the namespace created by the class definition; we’ll learn more about class objects in the next section.
[src:python/classes] The original local scope (the one in effect just before the class definition was entered) is reinstated, and the class object is bound here to the class name given in the class definition header (`ClassName` in the example).
[src:python/classes] Class objects support two kinds of operations: attribute references and instantiation.
[src:python/classes] then `MyClass.i` and `MyClass.f` are valid attribute references, returning an integer and a function object, respectively.
[src:python/classes] Class attributes can also be assigned to, so you can change the value of `MyClass.i` by assignment.
[src:python/classes] `__doc__` is also a valid attribute, returning the docstring belonging to the class: `"A simple example class"`.
[src:python/classes] Class *instantiation* uses function notation.
[src:python/classes] Just pretend that the class object is a parameterless function that returns a new instance of the class.
[src:python/classes] creates a new *instance* of the class and assigns this object to the local variable `x`.
[src:python/classes] The instantiation operation (“calling” a class object) creates an empty object.
[src:python/classes] Many classes like to create objects with instances customized to a specific initial state.
[src:python/classes] When a class defines an `__init__()` method, class instantiation automatically invokes `__init__()` for the newly created class instance.
[src:python/classes] Of course, the `__init__()` method may have arguments for greater flexibility.
[src:python/classes] In that case, arguments given to the class instantiation operator are passed on to `__init__()`.
[src:python/classes] Now what can we do with instance objects?
[src:python/classes] The only operations understood by instance objects are attribute references.
[src:python/classes] There are two kinds of valid attribute names: data attributes and methods.
[src:python/classes] The other kind of instance attribute reference is a *method*.
[src:python/classes] A method is a function that “belongs to” an object.
[src:python/classes] Valid method names of an instance object depend on its class.
[src:python/classes] By definition, all attributes of a class that are function objects define corresponding methods of its instances.
[src:python/classes] So in our example, `x.f` is a valid method reference, since `MyClass.f` is a function, but `x.i` is not, since `MyClass.i` is not.
[src:python/classes] But `x.f` is not the same thing as `MyClass.f` — it is a *method object*, not a function object.
[src:python/classes] If `x = MyClass()`, as above, this will return the string `'hello world'`.
[src:python/classes] However, it is not necessary to call a method right away: `x.f` is a method object, and can be stored away and called at a later time.
[src:python/classes] will continue to print `hello world` until the end of time.
[src:python/classes] What exactly happens when a method is called?
[src:python/classes] You may have noticed that `x.f()` was called without an argument above, even though the function definition for `f()` specified an argument.
[src:python/classes] Actually, you may have guessed the answer: the special thing about methods is that the instance object is passed as the first argument of the function.
[src:python/classes] In our example, the call `x.f()` is exactly equivalent to `MyClass.f(x)`.
[src:python/classes] In general, calling a method with a list of *n* arguments is equivalent to calling the corresponding function with an argument list that is created by inserting the method’s instance object before the first argument.
[src:python/classes] When a non-data attribute of an instance is referenced, the instance’s class is searched.
[src:python/classes] If the name denotes a valid class attribute that is a function object, references to both the instance object and the function object are packed into a method object.
[src:python/classes] When the method object is called with an argument list, a new argument list is constructed from the instance object and the argument list, and the function object is called with this new argument list.
[src:python/classes] As discussed in A Word About Names and Objects, shared data can have possibly surprising effects involving mutable objects such as lists and dictionaries.
[src:python/classes] Data attributes may be referenced by methods as well as by ordinary users (“clients”) of an object.
[src:python/classes] In other words, classes are not usable to implement pure abstract data types.
[src:python/classes] In fact, nothing in Python makes it possible to enforce data hiding — it is all based upon convention.
[src:python/classes] Clients should use data attributes with care — clients may mess up invariants maintained by the methods by stamping on their data attributes.
[src:python/classes] Note that clients may add data attributes of their own to an instance object without affecting the validity of the methods, as long as name conflicts are avoided — again, a naming convention can save a lot of headaches here.
[src:python/classes] There is no shorthand for referencing data attributes (or other methods!) from within methods.
[src:python/classes] I find that this actually increases the readability of methods: there is no chance of confusing local variables and instance variables when glancing through a method.
[src:python/classes] Often, the first argument of a method is called `self`.
[src:python/classes] This is nothing more than a convention: the name `self` has absolutely no special meaning to Python.
[src:python/classes] Note, however, that by not following the convention your code may be less readable to other Python programmers, and it is also conceivable that a *class browser* program might be written that relies upon such a convention.
[src:python/classes] Any function object that is a class attribute defines a method for instances of that class.
[src:python/classes] It is not necessary that the function definition is textually enclosed in the class definition: assigning a function object to a local variable in the class is also ok.
[src:python/classes] Now `f`, `g` and `h` are all attributes of class `C` that refer to function objects, and consequently they are all methods of instances of `C` — `h` being exactly equivalent to `g`.
[src:python/classes] Note that this practice usually only serves to confuse the reader of a program.
[src:python/classes] Methods may reference global names in the same way as ordinary functions.
[src:python/classes] The global scope associated with a method is the module containing its definition.
[src:python/classes] Usually, the class containing the method is itself defined in this global scope, and in the next section we’ll find some good reasons why a method would want to reference its own class.
[src:python/classes] Each value is an object, and therefore has a *class* (also called its *type*).
[src:python/classes] Of course, a language feature would not be worthy of the name “class” without supporting inheritance.
[src:python/classes] The name `BaseClassName` must be defined in a namespace accessible from the scope containing the derived class definition.
[src:python/classes] In place of a base class name, other arbitrary expressions are also allowed.
[src:python/classes] Execution of a derived class definition proceeds the same as for a base class.
[src:python/classes] When the class object is constructed, the base class is remembered.
[src:python/classes] This is used for resolving attribute references: if a requested attribute is not found in the class, the search proceeds to look in the base class.
[src:python/classes] This rule is applied recursively if the base class itself is derived from some other class.
[src:python/classes] There’s nothing special about instantiation of derived classes: `DerivedClassName()` creates a new instance of the class.
[src:python/classes] Method references are resolved as follows: the corresponding class attribute is searched, descending down the chain of base classes if necessary, and the method reference is valid if this yields a function object.
[src:python/classes] Derived classes may override methods of their base classes.
[src:python/classes] Because methods have no special privileges when calling other methods of the same object, a method of a base class that calls another method defined in the same base class may end up calling a method of a derived class that overrides it.
[src:python/classes] An overriding method in a derived class may in fact want to extend rather than simply replace the base class method of the same name.
[src:python/classes] There is a simple way to call the base class method directly: just call `BaseClassName.methodname(self, arguments)`.
[src:python/classes] This is occasionally useful to clients as well.
[src:python/classes] Python supports a form of multiple inheritance as well.
[src:python/classes] For most purposes, in the simplest cases, you can think of the search for attributes inherited from a parent class as depth-first, left-to-right, not searching twice in the same class where there is an overlap in the hierarchy.
[src:python/classes] Thus, if an attribute is not found in `DerivedClassName`, it is searched for in `Base1`, then (recursively) in the base classes of `Base1`, and if it was not found there, it was searched for in `Base2`, and so on.
[src:python/classes] In fact, it is slightly more complex than that; the method resolution order changes dynamically to support cooperative calls to `super()`.
[src:python/classes] This approach is known in some other multiple-inheritance languages as call-next-method and is more powerful than the super call found in single-inheritance languages.
[src:python/classes] Dynamic ordering is necessary because all cases of multiple inheritance exhibit one or more diamond relationships (where at least one of the parent classes can be accessed through multiple paths from the bottommost class).
[src:python/classes] For example, all classes inherit from `object`, so any case of multiple inheritance provides more than one path to reach `object`.
[src:python/classes] Taken together, these properties make it possible to design reliable and extensible classes with multiple inheritance.
[src:python/classes] For more detail, see The Python 2.3 Method Resolution Order.
[src:python/classes] “Private” instance variables that cannot be accessed except from inside an object don’t exist in Python.
[src:python/classes] However, there is a convention that is followed by most Python code: a name prefixed with an underscore (e.g.
[src:python/classes] `_spam`) should be treated as a non-public part of the API (whether it is a function, a method or a data member).
[src:python/classes] It should be considered an implementation detail and subject to change without notice.
[src:python/classes] Since there is a valid use-case for class-private members (namely to avoid name clashes of names with names defined by subclasses), there is limited support for such a mechanism, called *name mangling*.
[src:python/classes] Any identifier of the form `__spam` (at least two leading underscores, at most one trailing underscore) is textually replaced with `_classname__spam`, where `classname` is the current class name with leading underscore(s) stripped.
[src:python/classes] This mangling is done without regard to the syntactic position of the identifier, as long as it occurs within the definition of a class.
[src:python/classes] The private name mangling specifications for details and special cases.
[src:python/classes] Name mangling is helpful for letting subclasses override methods without breaking intraclass method calls.
[src:python/classes] The above example would work even if `MappingSubclass` were to introduce a `__update` identifier since it is replaced with `_Mapping__update` in the `Mapping` class and `_MappingSubclass__update` in the `MappingSubclass` class respectively.
[src:python/classes] Note that the mangling rules are designed mostly to avoid accidents; it still is possible to access or modify a variable that is considered private.
[src:python/classes] This can even be useful in special circumstances, such as in the debugger.
[src:python/classes] Notice that code passed to `exec()` or `eval()` does not consider the classname of the invoking class to be the current class; this is similar to the effect of the `global` statement, the effect of which is likewise restricted to code that is byte-compiled together.
[src:python/classes] The same restriction applies to `getattr()`, `setattr()` and `delattr()`, as well as when referencing `__dict__` directly.
[src:python/classes] Sometimes it is useful to have a data type similar to the Pascal “record” or C “struct”, bundling together a few named data items.
[src:python/classes] A piece of Python code that expects a particular abstract data type can often be passed a class that emulates the methods of that data type instead.
[src:python/classes] For instance, if you have a function that formats some data from a file object, you can define a class with methods `read()` and `readline()` that get the data from a string buffer instead, and pass it as an argument.
[src:python/classes] Instance method objects have attributes, too: `m.__self__` is the instance object with the method `m()`, and `m.__func__` is the function object corresponding to the method.
[src:python/classes] This style of access is clear, concise, and convenient.
[src:python/classes] The use of iterators pervades and unifies Python.
[src:python/classes] Behind the scenes, the `for` statement calls `iter()` on the container object.
[src:python/classes] The function returns an iterator object that defines the method `__next__()` which accesses elements in the container one at a time.
[src:python/classes] When there are no more elements, `__next__()` raises a `StopIteration` exception which tells the `for` loop to terminate.
[src:python/classes] Having seen the mechanics behind the iterator protocol, it is easy to add iterator behavior to your classes.
[src:python/classes] Define an `__iter__()` method which returns an object with a `__next__()` method.
[src:python/classes] Generators are a simple and powerful tool for creating iterators.
[src:python/classes] They are written like regular functions but use the `yield` statement whenever they want to return data.
[src:python/classes] Each time `next()` is called on it, the generator resumes where it left off (it remembers all the data values and which statement was last executed).
[src:python/classes] Anything that can be done with generators can also be done with class-based iterators as described in the previous section.
[src:python/classes] What makes generators so compact is that the `__iter__()` and `__next__()` methods are created automatically.
[src:python/classes] Another key feature is that the local variables and execution state are automatically saved between calls.
[src:python/classes] This made the function easier to write and much more clear than an approach using instance variables like `self.index` and `self.data`.
[src:python/classes] In addition to automatic method creation and saving program state, when generators terminate, they automatically raise `StopIteration`.
[src:python/classes] In combination, these features make it easy to create iterators with no more effort than writing a regular function.
[src:python/classes] Some simple generators can be coded succinctly as expressions using a syntax similar to list comprehensions but with parentheses instead of square brackets.
[src:python/classes] These expressions are designed for situations where the generator is used right away by an enclosing function.
[src:python/classes] Generator expressions are more compact but less versatile than full generator definitions and tend to be more memory friendly than equivalent list comprehensions.
[src:python/collections] This module implements specialized container datatypes providing alternatives to Python’s general purpose built-in containers, `dict`, `list`, `set`, and `tuple`.
[src:python/collections] A `ChainMap` class is provided for quickly linking a number of mappings so they can be treated as a single unit.
[src:python/collections] It is often much faster than creating a new dictionary and running multiple `update()` calls.
[src:python/collections] The class can be used to simulate nested scopes and is useful in templating.
[src:python/collections] A `ChainMap` groups multiple dicts or other mappings together to create a single, updateable view.
[src:python/collections] If no *maps* are specified, a single empty dictionary is provided so that a new chain always has at least one mapping.
[src:python/collections] The underlying mappings are stored in a list.
[src:python/collections] That list is public and can be accessed or updated using the *maps* attribute.
[src:python/collections] Lookups search the underlying mappings successively until a key is found.
[src:python/collections] In contrast, writes, updates, and deletions only operate on the first mapping.
[src:python/collections] A `ChainMap` incorporates the underlying mappings by reference.
[src:python/collections] So, if one of the underlying mappings gets updated, those changes will be reflected in `ChainMap`.
[src:python/collections] All of the usual dictionary methods are supported.
[src:python/collections] The list is ordered from first-searched to last-searched.
[src:python/collections] It is the only stored state and can be modified to change which mappings are searched.
[src:python/collections] The list should always contain at least one mapping.
[src:python/collections] Returns a new `ChainMap` containing a new map followed by all of the maps in the current instance.
[src:python/collections] If `m` is specified, it becomes the new map at the front of the list of mappings; if not specified, an empty dict is used, so that a call to `d.new_child()` is equivalent to: `ChainMap({}, *d.maps)`.
[src:python/collections] If any keyword arguments are specified, they update passed map or new empty dict.
[src:python/collections] This method is used for creating subcontexts that can be updated without altering values in any of the parent mappings.
[src:python/collections] Changed in version 3.4: The optional `m` parameter was added.
[src:python/collections] Changed in version 3.10: Keyword arguments support was added.
[src:python/collections] Property returning a new `ChainMap` containing all of the maps in the current instance except the first one.
[src:python/collections] This is useful for skipping the first map in the search.
[src:python/collections] Use cases are similar to those for the `nonlocal` keyword used in nested scopes.
[src:python/collections] The use cases also parallel those for the built-in `super()` function.
[src:python/collections] A reference to `d.parents` is equivalent to: `ChainMap(*d.maps[1:])`.
[src:python/collections] Changed in version 3.9: Added support for `|` and `|=` operators, specified in **PEP 584**.
[src:python/collections] This section shows various approaches to working with chained maps.
[src:python/collections] The `ChainMap` class only makes updates (writes and deletions) to the first mapping in the chain while lookups will search the full chain.
[src:python/collections] A counter tool is provided to support convenient and rapid tallies.
[src:python/collections] A `Counter` is a `dict` subclass for counting hashable objects.
[src:python/collections] It is a collection where elements are stored as dictionary keys and their counts are stored as dictionary values.
[src:python/collections] Counts are allowed to be any integer value including zero or negative counts.
[src:python/collections] The `Counter` class is similar to bags or multisets in other languages.
[src:python/collections] Setting a count to zero does not remove an element from a counter.
[src:python/collections] Changed in version 3.7: As a `dict` subclass, `Counter` inherited the capability to remember insertion order.
[src:python/collections] Math operations on *Counter* objects also preserve order.
[src:python/collections] Results are ordered according to when an element is first encountered in the left operand and then by the order encountered in the right operand.
[src:python/collections] Return an iterator over elements repeating each as many times as its count.
[src:python/collections] Elements are returned in the order first encountered.
[src:python/collections] If an element’s count is less than one, `elements()` will ignore it.
[src:python/collections] Return a list of the *n* most common elements and their counts from the most common to the least.
[src:python/collections] If *n* is omitted or `None`, `most_common()` returns *all* elements in the counter.
[src:python/collections] Elements are subtracted from an *iterable* or from another *mapping* (or counter).
[src:python/collections] Like `dict.update()` but subtracts counts instead of replacing them.
[src:python/collections] Both inputs and outputs may be zero or negative.
[src:python/collections] The usual dictionary methods are available for `Counter` objects except for two which work differently for counters.
[src:python/collections] This class method is not implemented for `Counter` objects.
[src:python/collections] Elements are counted from an *iterable* or added-in from another *mapping* (or counter).
[src:python/collections] Like `dict.update()` but adds counts instead of replacing them.
[src:python/collections] Also, the *iterable* is expected to be a sequence of elements, not a sequence of `(key, value)` pairs.
[src:python/collections] Counters support rich comparison operators for equality, subset, and superset relationships: `==`, `!=`, `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=`.
[src:python/collections] All of those tests treat missing elements as having zero counts so that `Counter(a=1) == Counter(a=1, b=0)` returns true.
[src:python/collections] Changed in version 3.10: Rich comparison operations were added.
[src:python/collections] Changed in version 3.10: In equality tests, missing elements are treated as having zero counts.
[src:python/collections] Formerly, `Counter(a=3)` and `Counter(a=3, b=0)` were considered distinct.
[src:python/collections] Several mathematical operations are provided for combining `Counter` objects to produce multisets (counters that have counts greater than zero).
[src:python/collections] Addition and subtraction combine counters by adding or subtracting the counts of corresponding elements.
[src:python/collections] Intersection and union return the minimum and maximum of corresponding counts.
[src:python/collections] Equality and inclusion compare corresponding counts.
[src:python/collections] Each operation can accept inputs with signed counts, but the output will exclude results with counts of zero or less.
[src:python/collections] Unary addition and subtraction are shortcuts for adding an empty counter or subtracting from an empty counter.
[src:python/collections] Added in version 3.3: Added support for unary plus, unary minus, and in-place multiset operations.
[src:python/collections] Counters were primarily designed to work with positive integers to represent running counts; however, care was taken to not unnecessarily preclude use cases needing other types or negative values.
[src:python/collections] To help with those use cases, this section documents the minimum range and type restrictions.
[src:python/collections] Returns a new deque object initialized left-to-right (using `append()`) with data from *iterable*.
[src:python/collections] If *iterable* is not specified, the new deque is empty.
[src:python/collections] Deques are a generalization of stacks and queues (the name is pronounced “deck” and is short for “double-ended queue”).
[src:python/collections] Deques support thread-safe, memory efficient appends and pops from either side of the deque with approximately the same *O*(1) performance in either direction.
[src:python/collections] Though `list` objects support similar operations, they are optimized for fast fixed-length operations and incur *O*(*n*) memory movement costs for `pop(0)` and `insert(0, v)` operations which change both the size and position of the underlying data representation.
[src:python/collections] If *maxlen* is not specified or is `None`, deques may grow to an arbitrary length.
[src:python/collections] Otherwise, the deque is bounded to the specified maximum length.
[src:python/collections] Once a bounded length deque is full, when new items are added, a corresponding number of items are discarded from the opposite end.
[src:python/collections] Bounded length deques provide functionality similar to the `tail` filter in Unix.
[src:python/collections] They are also useful for tracking transactions and other pools of data where only the most recent activity is of interest.
[src:python/collections] Deques are generic over the type of their contents.
[src:python/collections] Add *item* to the right side of the deque.
[src:python/collections] Add *item* to the left side of the deque.
[src:python/collections] Remove all elements from the deque leaving it with length 0.
[src:python/collections] Count the number of deque elements equal to *value*.
[src:python/collections] Extend the right side of the deque by appending elements from the iterable argument.
[src:python/collections] Extend the left side of the deque by appending elements from *iterable*.
[src:python/collections] Note, the series of left appends results in reversing the order of elements in the iterable argument.
[src:python/collections] Return the position of *value* in the deque (at or after index *start* and before index *stop*).
[src:python/collections] Returns the first match or raises `ValueError` if not found.
[src:python/collections] Insert *value* into the deque at position *index*.
[src:python/collections] If the insertion would cause a bounded deque to grow beyond *maxlen*, an `IndexError` is raised.
[src:python/collections] Remove and return an element from the right side of the deque.
[src:python/collections] If no elements are present, raises an `IndexError`.
[src:python/collections] Remove and return an element from the left side of the deque.
[src:python/collections] Reverse the elements of the deque in-place and then return `None`.
[src:python/collections] Rotate the deque *n* steps to the right.
[src:python/collections] When the deque is not empty, rotating one step to the right is equivalent to `d.appendleft(d.pop())`, and rotating one step to the left is equivalent to `d.append(d.popleft())`.
[src:python/collections] Maximum size of a deque or `None` if unbounded.
[src:python/collections] In addition to the above, deques support iteration, pickling, `len(d)`, `reversed(d)`, `copy.copy(d)`, `copy.deepcopy(d)`, membership testing with the `in` operator, and subscript references such as `d[0]` to access the first element.
[src:python/collections] Indexed access is *O*(1) at both ends but slows to *O*(*n*) in the middle.
[src:python/collections] For fast random access, use lists instead.
[src:python/collections] This section shows various approaches to working with deques.
[src:python/collections] A round-robin scheduler can be implemented with input iterators stored in a `deque`.
[src:python/collections] Values are yielded from the active iterator in position zero.
[src:python/collections] The `rotate()` method provides a way to implement `deque` slicing and deletion.
[src:python/collections] To implement `deque` slicing, use a similar approach applying `rotate()` to bring a target element to the left side of the deque.
[src:python/collections] Remove old entries with `popleft()`, add new entries with `extend()`, and then reverse the rotation.
[src:python/collections] With minor variations on that approach, it is easy to implement Forth style stack manipulations such as `dup`, `drop`, `swap`, `over`, `pick`, `rot`, and `roll`.
[src:python/collections] `defaultdict` is a subclass of the built-in `dict` class.
[src:python/collections] It overrides one method and adds one writable instance variable.
[src:python/collections] The remaining functionality is the same as for the `dict` class and is not documented here.
[src:python/collections] The first argument provides the initial value for the `default_factory` attribute; it defaults to `None`.
[src:python/collections] All remaining arguments are treated the same as if they were passed to the `dict` constructor, including keyword arguments.
[src:python/collections] `defaultdict`s are generic over two types, signifying (respectively) the types of the dictionary’s keys and values.
[src:python/collections] If the `default_factory` attribute is `None`, this raises a `KeyError` exception with the *key* as argument.
[src:python/collections] If `default_factory` is not `None`, it is called without arguments to provide a default value for the given *key*, this value is inserted in the dictionary for the *key*, and returned.
[src:python/collections] If calling `default_factory` raises an exception this exception is propagated unchanged.
[src:python/collections] This method is called by the `__getitem__()` method of the `dict` class when the requested key is not found; whatever it returns or raises is then returned or raised by `__getitem__()`.
[src:python/collections] Note that `__missing__()` is *not* called for any operations besides `__getitem__()`.
[src:python/collections] This means that `get()` will, like normal dictionaries, return `None` as a default rather than using `default_factory`.
[src:python/collections] This attribute is used by the `__missing__()` method; it is initialized from the first argument to the constructor, if present, or to `None`, if absent.
[src:python/collections] Changed in version 3.9: Added merge (`|`) and update (`|=`) operators, specified in **PEP 584**.
[src:python/collections] When each key is encountered for the first time, it is not already in the mapping; so an entry is automatically created using the `default_factory` function which returns an empty `list`.
[src:python/collections] The `list.append()` operation then attaches the value to the new list.
[src:python/collections] When keys are encountered again, the look-up proceeds normally (returning the list for that key) and the `list.append()` operation adds another value to the list.
[src:python/collections] When a letter is first encountered, it is missing from the mapping, so the `default_factory` function calls `int()` to supply a default count of zero.
[src:python/collections] The increment operation then builds up the count for each letter.
[src:python/collections] The function `int()` which always returns zero is just a special case of constant functions.
[src:python/collections] Named tuples assign meaning to each position in a tuple and allow for more readable, self-documenting code.
[src:python/collections] They can be used wherever regular tuples are used, and they add the ability to access fields by name instead of position index.
[src:python/collections] Returns a new tuple subclass named *typename*.
[src:python/collections] The new subclass is used to create tuple-like objects that have fields accessible by attribute lookup as well as being indexable and iterable.
[src:python/collections] Instances of the subclass also have a helpful docstring (with *typename* and *field_names*) and a helpful `__repr__()` method which lists the tuple contents in a `name=value` format.
[src:python/collections] The *field_names* are a sequence of strings such as `['x', 'y']`.
[src:python/collections] Alternatively, *field_names* can be a single string with each fieldname separated by whitespace and/or commas, for example `'x y'` or `'x, y'`.
[src:python/collections] Any valid Python identifier may be used for a fieldname except for names starting with an underscore.
[src:python/collections] Valid identifiers consist of letters, digits, and underscores but do not start with a digit or underscore and cannot be a `keyword` such as *class*, *for*, *return*, *global*, *pass*, or *raise*.
[src:python/collections] If *rename* is true, invalid fieldnames are automatically replaced with positional names.
[src:python/collections] For example, `['abc', 'def', 'ghi', 'abc']` is converted to `['abc', '_1', 'ghi', '_3']`, eliminating the keyword `def` and the duplicate fieldname `abc`.
[src:python/collections] If *module* is defined, the `__module__` attribute of the named tuple is set to that value.
[src:python/collections] Named tuple instances do not have per-instance dictionaries, so they are lightweight and require no more memory than regular tuples.
[src:python/collections] To support pickling, the named tuple class should be assigned to a variable that matches *typename*.
