[src:python/controlflow] As well as the `while` statement just introduced, Python uses a few more that we will encounter in this chapter.
[src:python/controlflow] Perhaps the most well-known statement type is the `if` statement.
[src:python/controlflow] There can be zero or more `elif` parts, and the `else` part is optional.
[src:python/controlflow] The keyword ‘`elif`’ is short for ‘else if’, and is useful to avoid excessive indentation.
[src:python/controlflow] An `if` … `elif` … `elif` … sequence is a substitute for the `switch` or `case` statements found in other languages.
[src:python/controlflow] If you’re comparing the same value to several constants, or checking for specific types or attributes, you may also find the `match` statement useful.
[src:python/controlflow] The `for` statement in Python differs a bit from what you may be used to in C or Pascal.
[src:python/controlflow] Code that modifies a collection while iterating over that same collection can be tricky to get right.
[src:python/controlflow] If you do need to iterate over a sequence of numbers, the built-in function `range()` comes in handy.
[src:python/controlflow] The given end point is never part of the generated sequence; `range(10)` generates 10 values, the legal indices for items of a sequence of length 10.
[src:python/controlflow] In most such cases, however, it is convenient to use the `enumerate()` function, see Looping Techniques.
[src:python/controlflow] In many ways the object returned by `range()` behaves as if it is a list, but in fact it isn’t.
[src:python/controlflow] It is an object which returns the successive items of the desired sequence when you iterate over it, but it doesn’t really make the list, thus saving space.
[src:python/controlflow] We say such an object is iterable, that is, suitable as a target for functions and constructs that expect something from which they can obtain successive items until the supply is exhausted.
[src:python/controlflow] Later we will see more functions that return iterables and take iterables as arguments.
[src:python/controlflow] In chapter Data Structures, we will discuss `list()` in more detail.
[src:python/controlflow] In a `for` or `while` loop the `break` statement may be paired with an `else` clause.
[src:python/controlflow] If the loop finishes without executing the `break`, the `else` clause executes.
[src:python/controlflow] In a `for` loop, the `else` clause is executed after the loop finishes its final iteration, that is, if no break occurred.
[src:python/controlflow] In a `while` loop, it’s executed after the loop’s condition becomes false.
[src:python/controlflow] In either kind of loop, the `else` clause is **not** executed if the loop was terminated by a `break`.
[src:python/controlflow] Of course, other ways of ending the loop early, such as a `return` or a raised exception, will also skip execution of the `else` clause.
[src:python/controlflow] One way to think of the else clause is to imagine it paired with the `if` inside the loop.
[src:python/controlflow] As the loop executes, it will run a sequence like if/if/if/else.
[src:python/controlflow] The `if` is inside the loop, encountered a number of times.
[src:python/controlflow] If the condition is ever true, a `break` will happen.
[src:python/controlflow] If the condition is never true, the `else` clause outside the loop will execute.
[src:python/controlflow] When used with a loop, the `else` clause has more in common with the `else` clause of a `try` statement than it does with that of `if` statements: a `try` statement’s `else` clause runs when no exception occurs, and a loop’s `else` clause runs when no `break` occurs.
[src:python/controlflow] For more on the `try` statement and exceptions, see Handling Exceptions.
[src:python/controlflow] It can be used when a statement is required syntactically but the program requires no action.
[src:python/controlflow] Another place `pass` can be used is as a place-holder for a function or conditional body when you are working on new code, allowing you to keep thinking at a more abstract level.
[src:python/controlflow] For this last case, many people use the ellipsis literal `...` instead of `pass`.
[src:python/controlflow] This use has no special meaning to Python, and is not part of the language definition (you could use any constant expression here), but `...` is used conventionally as a placeholder body as well.
[src:python/controlflow] A `match` statement takes an expression and compares its value to successive patterns given as one or more case blocks.
[src:python/controlflow] This is superficially similar to a switch statement in C, Java or JavaScript (and many other languages), but it’s more similar to pattern matching in languages like Rust or Haskell.
[src:python/controlflow] Only the first pattern that matches gets executed and it can also extract components (sequence elements or object attributes) from the value into variables.
[src:python/controlflow] If no case matches, none of the branches is executed.
[src:python/controlflow] Note the last block: the “variable name” `_` acts as a *wildcard* and never fails to match.
[src:python/controlflow] The first pattern has two literals, and can be thought of as an extension of the literal pattern shown above.
[src:python/controlflow] But the next two patterns combine a literal and a variable, and the variable *binds* a value from the subject (`point`).
[src:python/controlflow] The fourth pattern captures two values, which makes it conceptually similar to the unpacking assignment `(x, y) = point`.
[src:python/controlflow] You can use positional parameters with some builtin classes that provide an ordering for their attributes (e.g. dataclasses).
[src:python/controlflow] You can also define a specific position for attributes in patterns by setting the `__match_args__` special attribute in your classes.
[src:python/controlflow] A recommended way to read patterns is to look at them as an extended form of what you would put on the left of an assignment, to understand which variables would be set to what.
[src:python/controlflow] Only the standalone names (like `var` above) are assigned to by a match statement.
[src:python/controlflow] Dotted names (like `foo.bar`), attribute names (the `x=` and `y=` above) or class names (recognized by the “(…)” next to them like `Point` above) are never assigned to.
[src:python/controlflow] We can add an `if` clause to a pattern, known as a “guard”.
[src:python/controlflow] If the guard is false, `match` goes on to try the next case block.
[src:python/controlflow] For a more detailed explanation and additional examples, you can look into **PEP 636** which is written in a tutorial format.
[src:python/controlflow] The keyword `def` introduces a function *definition*.
[src:python/controlflow] It must be followed by the function name and the parenthesized list of formal parameters.
[src:python/controlflow] The statements that form the body of the function start at the next line, and must be indented.
[src:python/controlflow] The first statement of the function body can optionally be a string literal; this string literal is the function’s documentation string, or *docstring*.
[src:python/controlflow] The *execution* of a function introduces a new symbol table used for the local variables of the function.
[src:python/controlflow] More precisely, all variable assignments in a function store the value in the local symbol table; whereas variable references first look in the local symbol table, then in the local symbol tables of enclosing functions, then in the global symbol table, and finally in the table of built-in names.
[src:python/controlflow] Thus, global variables and variables of enclosing functions cannot be directly assigned a value within a function (unless, for global variables, named in a `global` statement, or, for variables of enclosing functions, named in a `nonlocal` statement), although they may be referenced.
[src:python/controlflow] A function definition associates the function name with the function object in the current symbol table.
[src:python/controlflow] The interpreter recognizes the object pointed to by that name as a user-defined function.
[src:python/controlflow] Coming from other languages, you might object that `fib` is not a function but a procedure since it doesn’t return a value.
[src:python/controlflow] In fact, even functions without a `return` statement do return a value, albeit a rather boring one.
[src:python/controlflow] This value is called `None` (it’s a built-in name).
[src:python/controlflow] Writing the value `None` is normally suppressed by the interpreter if it would be the only value written.
[src:python/controlflow] It is also possible to define functions with a variable number of arguments.
[src:python/controlflow] There are three forms, which can be combined.
[src:python/controlflow] The most useful form is to specify a default value for one or more arguments.
[src:python/controlflow] This creates a function that can be called with fewer arguments than it is defined to allow.
[src:python/controlflow] This example also introduces the `in` keyword.
[src:python/controlflow] This tests whether or not a sequence contains a certain value.
[src:python/controlflow] Functions can also be called using keyword arguments of the form `kwarg=value`.
[src:python/controlflow] accepts one required argument (`voltage`) and three optional arguments (`state`, `action`, and `type`).
[src:python/controlflow] In a function call, keyword arguments must follow positional arguments.
[src:python/controlflow] All the keyword arguments passed must match one of the arguments accepted by the function (e.g.
[src:python/controlflow] `actor` is not a valid argument for the `parrot` function), and their order is not important.
[src:python/controlflow] This also includes non-optional arguments (e.g.
[src:python/controlflow] No argument may receive a value more than once.
[src:python/controlflow] When a final formal parameter of the form `**name` is present, it receives a dictionary (see Mapping Types — dict) containing all keyword arguments except for those corresponding to a formal parameter.
[src:python/controlflow] This may be combined with a formal parameter of the form `*name` (described in the next subsection) which receives a tuple containing the positional arguments beyond the formal parameter list.
[src:python/controlflow] Note that the order in which the keyword arguments are printed is guaranteed to match the order in which they were provided in the function call.
[src:python/controlflow] By default, arguments may be passed to a Python function either by position or explicitly by keyword.
[src:python/controlflow] For readability and performance, it makes sense to restrict the way arguments can be passed so that a developer need only look at the function definition to determine if items are passed by position, by position or keyword, or by keyword.
[src:python/controlflow] If used, these symbols indicate the kind of parameter by how the arguments may be passed to the function: positional-only, positional-or-keyword, and keyword-only.
[src:python/controlflow] Keyword parameters are also referred to as named parameters.
[src:python/controlflow] If `/` and `*` are not present in the function definition, arguments may be passed to a function by position or by keyword.
[src:python/controlflow] Looking at this in a bit more detail, it is possible to mark certain parameters as *positional-only*.
[src:python/controlflow] If *positional-only*, the parameters’ order matters, and the parameters cannot be passed by keyword.
[src:python/controlflow] Positional-only parameters are placed before a `/` (forward-slash).
[src:python/controlflow] The `/` is used to logically separate the positional-only parameters from the rest of the parameters.
[src:python/controlflow] If there is no `/` in the function definition, there are no positional-only parameters.
[src:python/controlflow] Parameters following the `/` may be *positional-or-keyword* or *keyword-only*.
[src:python/controlflow] To mark parameters as *keyword-only*, indicating the parameters must be passed by keyword argument, place an `*` in the arguments list just before the first *keyword-only* parameter.
[src:python/controlflow] There is no possible call that will make it return `True` as the keyword `'name'` will always bind to the first parameter.
[src:python/controlflow] In other words, the names of positional-only parameters can be used in `**kwds` without ambiguity.
[src:python/controlflow] Finally, the least frequently used option is to specify that a function can be called with an arbitrary number of arguments.
[src:python/controlflow] These arguments will be wrapped up in a tuple (see Tuples and Sequences).
[src:python/controlflow] Before the variable number of arguments, zero or more normal arguments may occur.
[src:python/controlflow] Normally, these *variadic* arguments will be last in the list of formal parameters, because they scoop up all remaining input arguments that are passed to the function.
[src:python/controlflow] Any formal parameters which occur after the `*args` parameter are ‘keyword-only’ arguments, meaning that they can only be used as keywords rather than positional arguments.
[src:python/controlflow] The reverse situation occurs when the arguments are already in a list or tuple but need to be unpacked for a function call requiring separate positional arguments.
[src:python/controlflow] For instance, the built-in `range()` function expects separate *start* and *stop* arguments.
[src:python/controlflow] Small anonymous functions can be created with the `lambda` keyword.
[src:python/controlflow] This function returns the sum of its two arguments: `lambda a, b: a+b`.
[src:python/controlflow] Lambda functions can be used wherever function objects are required.
[src:python/controlflow] They are syntactically restricted to a single expression.
[src:python/controlflow] Semantically, they are just syntactic sugar for a normal function definition.
[src:python/controlflow] The above example uses a lambda expression to return a function.
[src:python/controlflow] Another use is to pass a small function as an argument.
[src:python/controlflow] Here are some conventions about the content and formatting of documentation strings.
[src:python/controlflow] The first line should always be a short, concise summary of the object’s purpose.
[src:python/controlflow] For brevity, it should not explicitly state the object’s name or type, since these are available by other means (except if the name happens to be a verb describing a function’s operation).
[src:python/controlflow] This line should begin with a capital letter and end with a period.
[src:python/controlflow] If there are more lines in the documentation string, the second line should be blank, visually separating the summary from the rest of the description.
[src:python/controlflow] The following lines should be one or more paragraphs describing the object’s calling conventions, its side effects, etc.
[src:python/controlflow] The Python parser strips indentation from multi-line string literals when they serve as module, class, or function docstrings.
[src:python/controlflow] Function annotations are completely optional metadata information about the types used by user-defined functions (see **PEP 3107** and **PEP 484** for more information).
[src:python/controlflow] Annotations are stored in the `__annotations__` attribute of the function as a dictionary and have no effect on any other part of the function.
[src:python/controlflow] Parameter annotations are defined by a colon after the parameter name, followed by an expression evaluating to the value of the annotation.
[src:python/controlflow] Return annotations are defined by a literal `->`, followed by an expression, between the parameter list and the colon denoting the end of the `def` statement.
[src:python/controlflow] Now that you are about to write longer, more complex pieces of Python, it is a good time to talk about *coding style*.
[src:python/controlflow] Most languages can be written (or more concisely, *formatted*) in different styles; some are more readable than others.
[src:python/controlflow] Making it easy for others to read your code is always a good idea, and adopting a nice coding style helps tremendously for that.
[src:python/controlflow] For Python, **PEP 8** has emerged as the style guide that most projects adhere to; it promotes a very readable and eye-pleasing coding style.
[src:python/dataclasses] This module provides a decorator and functions for automatically adding generated special methods such as `__init__()` and `__repr__()` to user-defined classes.
[src:python/dataclasses] It was originally described in **PEP 557**.
[src:python/dataclasses] The member variables to use in these generated methods are defined using **PEP 526** type annotations.
[src:python/dataclasses] Note that this method is automatically added to the class: it is not directly specified in the `InventoryItem` definition shown above.
[src:python/dataclasses] When defined on the class, it will be called by the generated `__init__()`, normally as `self.__post_init__()`.
[src:python/dataclasses] However, if any `InitVar` fields are defined, they will also be passed to `__post_init__()` in the order they were defined in the class.
[src:python/dataclasses] If no `__init__()` method is generated, then `__post_init__()` will not automatically be called.
[src:python/dataclasses] Among other uses, this allows for initializing field values that depend on one or more other fields.
[src:python/dataclasses] The `__init__()` method generated by `@dataclass` does not call base class `__init__()` methods.
[src:python/dataclasses] Note, however, that in general the dataclass-generated `__init__()` methods don’t need to be called, since the derived dataclass will take care of initializing all fields of any base class that is a dataclass itself.
[src:python/dataclasses] See the section below on init-only variables for ways to pass parameters to `__post_init__()`.
[src:python/dataclasses] Also see the warning about how `replace()` handles `init=False` fields.
[src:python/dataclasses] One of the few places where `@dataclass` actually inspects the type of a field is to determine if a field is a class variable as defined in **PEP 526**.
[src:python/dataclasses] It does this by checking if the type of the field is `typing.ClassVar`.
[src:python/dataclasses] If a field is a `ClassVar`, it is excluded from consideration as a field and is ignored by the dataclass mechanisms.
[src:python/dataclasses] Such `ClassVar` pseudo-fields are not returned by the module-level `fields()` function.
[src:python/dataclasses] Another place where `@dataclass` inspects a type annotation is to determine if a field is an init-only variable.
[src:python/dataclasses] It does this by seeing if the type of a field is of type `InitVar`.
[src:python/dataclasses] If a field is an `InitVar`, it is considered a pseudo-field called an init-only field.
[src:python/dataclasses] As it is not a true field, it is not returned by the module-level `fields()` function.
[src:python/dataclasses] Init-only fields are added as parameters to the generated `__init__()` method, and are passed to the optional `__post_init__()` method.
[src:python/dataclasses] They are not otherwise used by dataclasses.
[src:python/dataclasses] In this case, `fields()` will return `Field` objects for `i` and `j`, but not for `database`.
[src:python/dataclasses] It is not possible to create truly immutable Python objects.
[src:python/dataclasses] However, by passing `frozen=True` to the `@dataclass` decorator you can emulate immutability.
[src:python/dataclasses] In that case, dataclasses will add `__setattr__()` and `__delattr__()` methods to the class.
[src:python/dataclasses] These methods will raise a `FrozenInstanceError` when invoked.
[src:python/dataclasses] There is a tiny performance penalty when using `frozen=True`: `__init__()` cannot use simple assignment to initialize fields, and must use `object.__setattr__()`.
[src:python/dataclasses] When the dataclass is being created by the `@dataclass` decorator, it looks through all of the class’s base classes in reverse MRO (that is, starting at `object`) and, for each dataclass that it finds, adds the fields from that base class to an ordered mapping of fields.
[src:python/dataclasses] After all of the base class fields are added, it adds its own fields to the ordered mapping.
[src:python/dataclasses] All of the generated methods will use this combined, calculated ordered mapping of fields.
[src:python/dataclasses] Because the fields are in insertion order, derived classes override base classes.
[src:python/dataclasses] The final list of fields is, in order, `x`, `y`, `z`.
[src:python/dataclasses] The final type of `x` is `int`, as specified in class `C`.
[src:python/dataclasses] After the parameters needed for `__init__()` are computed, any keyword-only parameters are moved to come after all regular (non-keyword-only) parameters.
[src:python/dataclasses] This is a requirement of how keyword-only parameters are implemented in Python: they must come after non-keyword-only parameters.
[src:python/dataclasses] Note that the parameters have been re-ordered from how they appear in the list of fields: parameters derived from regular fields are followed by parameters derived from keyword-only fields.
[src:python/dataclasses] The relative ordering of keyword-only parameters is maintained in the re-ordered `__init__()` parameter list.
[src:python/dataclasses] If a `field()` specifies a *default_factory*, it is called with zero arguments when a default value for the field is needed.
[src:python/dataclasses] If a field is excluded from `__init__()` (using `init=False`) and the field also specifies *default_factory*, then the default factory function will always be called from the generated `__init__()` function.
[src:python/dataclasses] This happens because there is no other way to give the field an initial value.
[src:python/dataclasses] Python stores default member variable values in class attributes.
[src:python/dataclasses] Note that the two instances of class `C` share the same class variable `x`, as expected.
[src:python/dataclasses] This has the same issue as the original example using class `C`.
[src:python/dataclasses] That is, two instances of class `D` that do not specify a value for `x` when creating a class instance will share the same copy of `x`.
[src:python/dataclasses] Because dataclasses just use normal Python class creation they also share this behavior.
[src:python/dataclasses] There is no general way for Data Classes to detect this condition.
[src:python/dataclasses] Instead, the `@dataclass` decorator will raise a `ValueError` if it detects an unhashable default parameter.
[src:python/dataclasses] The assumption is that if a value is unhashable, it is mutable.
[src:python/dataclasses] This is a partial solution, but it does protect against many common errors.
[src:python/dataclasses] Changed in version 3.11: Instead of looking for and disallowing objects of type `list`, `dict`, or `set`, unhashable objects are now not allowed as default values.
[src:python/dataclasses] Unhashability is used to approximate mutability.
[src:python/dataclasses] Note that if a field is annotated with a descriptor type, but is not assigned a descriptor object as its default value, the field will act like a normal field.
[src:python/datastructures] This chapter describes some things you’ve learned about already in more detail, and adds some new things as well.
[src:python/datastructures] The list data type has some more methods.
[src:python/datastructures] Extend the list by appending all the items from the iterable.
[src:python/datastructures] The first argument is the index of the element before which to insert, so `a.insert(0, x)` inserts at the front of the list, and `a.insert(len(a), x)` is equivalent to `a.append(x)`.
[src:python/datastructures] Remove the first item from the list whose value is equal to *value*.
[src:python/datastructures] It raises a `ValueError` if there is no such item.
[src:python/datastructures] Remove the item at the given position in the list, and return it.
[src:python/datastructures] If no index is specified, `a.pop()` removes and returns the last item in the list.
[src:python/datastructures] It raises an `IndexError` if the list is empty or the index is outside the list range.
[src:python/datastructures] Return zero-based index of the first occurrence of *value* in the list.
[src:python/datastructures] Raises a `ValueError` if there is no such item.
[src:python/datastructures] The optional arguments *start* and *end* are interpreted as in the slice notation and are used to limit the search to a particular subsequence of the list.
[src:python/datastructures] The returned index is computed relative to the beginning of the full sequence rather than the *start* argument.
[src:python/datastructures] Return the number of times *value* appears in the list.
[src:python/datastructures] Sort the items of the list in place (the arguments can be used for sort customization, see `sorted()` for their explanation).
[src:python/datastructures] Reverse the elements of the list in place.
[src:python/datastructures] You might have noticed that methods like `insert`, `remove` or `sort` that only modify the list have no return value printed – they return the default `None`. [1] This is a design principle for all mutable data structures in Python.
[src:python/datastructures] Another thing you might notice is that not all data can be sorted or compared.
[src:python/datastructures] For instance, `[None, 'hello', 10]` doesn’t sort because integers can’t be compared to strings and `None` can’t be compared to other types.
[src:python/datastructures] Also, there are some types that don’t have a defined ordering relation.
[src:python/datastructures] For example, `3+4j < 5+7j` isn’t a valid comparison.
[src:python/datastructures] The list methods make it very easy to use a list as a stack, where the last element added is the first element retrieved (“last-in, first-out”).
[src:python/datastructures] To add an item to the top of the stack, use `append()`.
[src:python/datastructures] To retrieve an item from the top of the stack, use `pop()` without an explicit index.
[src:python/datastructures] It is also possible to use a list as a queue, where the first element added is the first element retrieved (“first-in, first-out”); however, lists are not efficient for this purpose.
[src:python/datastructures] While appends and pops from the end of list are fast, doing inserts or pops from the beginning of a list is slow (because all of the other elements have to be shifted by one).
[src:python/datastructures] To implement a queue, use `collections.deque` which was designed to have fast appends and pops from both ends.
[src:python/datastructures] List comprehensions provide a concise way to create lists.
[src:python/datastructures] Common applications are to make new lists where each element is the result of some operations applied to each member of another sequence or iterable, or to create a subsequence of those elements that satisfy a certain condition.
[src:python/datastructures] Note that this creates (or overwrites) a variable named `x` that still exists after the loop completes.
[src:python/datastructures] A list comprehension consists of brackets containing an expression followed by a `for` clause, then zero or more `for` or `if` clauses.
[src:python/datastructures] The result will be a new list resulting from evaluating the expression in the context of the `for` and `if` clauses which follow it.
[src:python/datastructures] Note how the order of the `for` and `if` statements is the same in both these snippets.
[src:python/datastructures] If the expression is a tuple (e.g. the `(x, y)` in the previous example), it must be parenthesized.
[src:python/datastructures] The initial expression in a list comprehension can be any arbitrary expression, including another list comprehension.
[src:python/datastructures] In the real world, you should prefer built-in functions to complex flow statements.
[src:python/datastructures] See Unpacking Argument Lists for details on the asterisk in this line.
[src:python/datastructures] There is a way to remove an item from a list given its index instead of its value: the `del` statement.
[src:python/datastructures] This differs from the `pop()` method which returns a value.
[src:python/datastructures] The `del` statement can also be used to remove slices from a list or clear the entire list (which we did earlier by assignment of an empty list to the slice).
[src:python/datastructures] Referencing the name `a` hereafter is an error (at least until another value is assigned to it).
[src:python/datastructures] We saw that lists and strings have many common properties, such as indexing and slicing operations.
[src:python/datastructures] They are two examples of *sequence* data types (see Sequence Types — list, tuple, range).
[src:python/datastructures] Since Python is an evolving language, other sequence data types may be added.
[src:python/datastructures] There is also another standard sequence data type: the *tuple*.
[src:python/datastructures] As you see, on output tuples are always enclosed in parentheses, so that nested tuples are interpreted correctly; they may be input with or without surrounding parentheses, although often parentheses are necessary anyway (if the tuple is part of a larger expression).
[src:python/datastructures] It is not possible to assign to the individual items of a tuple, however it is possible to create tuples which contain mutable objects, such as lists.
[src:python/datastructures] Though tuples may seem similar to lists, they are often used in different situations and for different purposes.
[src:python/datastructures] Tuples are immutable, and usually contain a heterogeneous sequence of elements that are accessed via unpacking (see later in this section) or indexing (or even by attribute in the case of `namedtuples`).
[src:python/datastructures] Lists are mutable, and their elements are usually homogeneous and are accessed by iterating over the list.
[src:python/datastructures] A special problem is the construction of tuples containing 0 or 1 items: the syntax has some extra quirks to accommodate these.
[src:python/datastructures] Empty tuples are constructed by an empty pair of parentheses; a tuple with one item is constructed by following a value with a comma (it is not sufficient to enclose a single value in parentheses).
[src:python/datastructures] The statement `t = 12345, 54321, 'hello!'` is an example of *tuple packing*: the values `12345`, `54321` and `'hello!'` are packed together in a tuple.
[src:python/datastructures] This is called, appropriately enough, *sequence unpacking* and works for any sequence on the right-hand side.
[src:python/datastructures] Sequence unpacking requires that there are as many variables on the left side of the equals sign as there are elements in the sequence.
[src:python/datastructures] Note that multiple assignment is really just a combination of tuple packing and sequence unpacking.
[src:python/datastructures] Python also includes a data type for sets.
[src:python/datastructures] A set is an unordered collection with no duplicate elements.
[src:python/datastructures] Basic uses include membership testing and eliminating duplicate entries.
[src:python/datastructures] Set objects also support mathematical operations like union, intersection, difference, and symmetric difference.
[src:python/datastructures] Curly braces or the `set()` function can be used to create sets.
[src:python/datastructures] Note: to create an empty set you have to use `set()`, not `{}`; the latter creates an empty dictionary, a data structure that we discuss in the next section.
[src:python/datastructures] Because sets are unordered, iterating over them or printing them can produce the elements in a different order than you expect.
[src:python/datastructures] Another useful data type built into Python is the *dictionary* (see Mapping Types — dict).
[src:python/datastructures] Dictionaries are sometimes found in other languages as “associative memories” or “associative arrays”.
[src:python/datastructures] Unlike sequences, which are indexed by a range of numbers, dictionaries are indexed by *keys*, which can be any immutable type; strings and numbers can always be keys.
[src:python/datastructures] Tuples can be used as keys if they contain only strings, numbers, or tuples; if a tuple contains any mutable object either directly or indirectly, it cannot be used as a key.
[src:python/datastructures] You can’t use lists as keys, since lists can be modified in place using index assignments, slice assignments, or methods like `append()` and `extend()`.
[src:python/datastructures] It is best to think of a dictionary as a set of *key: value* pairs, with the requirement that the keys are unique (within one dictionary).
[src:python/datastructures] A pair of braces creates an empty dictionary: `{}`.
[src:python/datastructures] Placing a comma-separated list of key:value pairs within the braces adds initial key:value pairs to the dictionary; this is also the way dictionaries are written on output.
[src:python/datastructures] The main operations on a dictionary are storing a value with some key and extracting the value given the key.
[src:python/datastructures] It is also possible to delete a key:value pair with `del`.
[src:python/datastructures] If you store using a key that is already in use, the old value associated with that key is forgotten.
[src:python/datastructures] Extracting a value for a non-existent key by subscripting (`d[key]`) raises a `KeyError`.
[src:python/datastructures] To avoid getting this error when trying to access a possibly non-existent key, use the `get()` method instead, which returns `None` (or a specified default value) if the key is not in the dictionary.
[src:python/datastructures] Performing `list(d)` on a dictionary returns a list of all the keys used in the dictionary, in insertion order (if you want it sorted, just use `sorted(d)` instead).
[src:python/datastructures] To check whether a single key is in the dictionary, use the `in` keyword.
[src:python/datastructures] When looping through dictionaries, the key and corresponding value can be retrieved at the same time using the `items()` method.
[src:python/datastructures] When looping through a sequence, the position index and corresponding value can be retrieved at the same time using the `enumerate()` function.
[src:python/datastructures] To loop over two or more sequences at the same time, the entries can be paired with the `zip()` function.
[src:python/datastructures] To loop over a sequence in reverse, first specify the sequence in a forward direction and then call the `reversed()` function.
[src:python/datastructures] To loop over a sequence in sorted order, use the `sorted()` function which returns a new sorted list while leaving the source unaltered.
[src:python/datastructures] Using `set()` on a sequence eliminates duplicate elements.
[src:python/datastructures] The use of `sorted()` in combination with `set()` over a sequence is an idiomatic way to loop over unique elements of the sequence in sorted order.
[src:python/datastructures] It is sometimes tempting to change a list while you are looping over it; however, it is often simpler and safer to create a new list instead.
[src:python/datastructures] The conditions used in `while` and `if` statements can contain any operators, not just comparisons.
[src:python/datastructures] The comparison operators `in` and `not in` are membership tests that determine whether a value is in (or not in) a container.
[src:python/datastructures] The operators `is` and `is not` compare whether two objects are really the same object.
[src:python/datastructures] All comparison operators have the same priority, which is lower than that of all numerical operators.
[src:python/datastructures] For example, `a < b == c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and moreover `b` equals `c`.
[src:python/datastructures] Comparisons may be combined using the Boolean operators `and` and `or`, and the outcome of a comparison (or of any other Boolean expression) may be negated with `not`.
[src:python/datastructures] These have lower priorities than comparison operators; between them, `not` has the highest priority and `or` the lowest, so that `A and not B or C` is equivalent to `(A and (not B)) or C`.
[src:python/datastructures] As always, parentheses can be used to express the desired composition.
[src:python/datastructures] The Boolean operators `and` and `or` are so-called *short-circuit* operators: their arguments are evaluated from left to right, and evaluation stops as soon as the outcome is determined.
[src:python/datastructures] For example, if `A` and `C` are true but `B` is false, `A and B and C` does not evaluate the expression `C`.
[src:python/datastructures] When used as a general value and not as a Boolean, the return value of a short-circuit operator is the last evaluated argument.
[src:python/datastructures] It is possible to assign the result of a comparison or other Boolean expression to a variable.
[src:python/datastructures] Note that in Python, unlike C, assignment inside expressions must be done explicitly with the walrus operator `:=`.
[src:python/datastructures] This avoids a common class of problems encountered in C programs: typing `=` in an expression when `==` was intended.
[src:python/datastructures] Sequence objects typically may be compared to other objects with the same sequence type.
[src:python/datastructures] The comparison uses *lexicographical* ordering: first the first two items are compared, and if they differ this determines the outcome of the comparison; if they are equal, the next two items are compared, and so on, until either sequence is exhausted.
[src:python/datastructures] If two items to be compared are themselves sequences of the same type, the lexicographical comparison is carried out recursively.
[src:python/datastructures] If all items of two sequences compare equal, the sequences are considered equal.
[src:python/datastructures] If one sequence is an initial sub-sequence of the other, the shorter sequence is the smaller (lesser) one.
[src:python/datastructures] Lexicographical ordering for strings uses the Unicode code point number to order individual characters.
[src:python/datastructures] Note that comparing objects of different types with `<` or `>` is legal provided that the objects have appropriate comparison methods.
[src:python/datastructures] For example, mixed numeric types are compared according to their numeric value, so 0 equals 0.0, etc.
[src:python/datastructures] Otherwise, rather than providing an arbitrary ordering, the interpreter will raise a `TypeError` exception.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The `datetime` module supplies classes for manipulating dates and times.
[src:python/datetime-p01] While date and time arithmetic is supported, the focus of the implementation is on efficient attribute extraction for output formatting and manipulation.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Concrete time zones representing the IANA time zone database.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Third-party library with expanded time zone and parsing support.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Third-party library that introduces distinct static types to for example, allow static type checkers to differentiate between naive and aware datetimes.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Date and time objects may be categorized as “aware” or “naive” depending on whether or not they include time zone information.
[src:python/datetime-p01] With sufficient knowledge of applicable algorithmic and political time adjustments, such as time zone and daylight saving time information, an **aware** object can locate itself relative to other aware objects.
[src:python/datetime-p01] A **naive** object does not contain enough information to unambiguously locate itself relative to other date/time objects.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Whether a naive object represents Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), local time, or time in some other time zone is purely up to the program, just like it is up to the program whether a particular number represents metres, miles, or mass.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Naive objects are easy to understand and to work with, at the cost of ignoring some aspects of reality.
[src:python/datetime-p01] For applications requiring aware objects, `datetime` and `time` objects have an optional time zone information attribute, `tzinfo`, that can be set to an instance of a subclass of the abstract `tzinfo` class.
[src:python/datetime-p01] These `tzinfo` objects capture information about the offset from UTC time, the time zone name, and whether daylight saving time is in effect.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Only one concrete `tzinfo` class, the `timezone` class, is supplied by the `datetime` module.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The `timezone` class can represent simple time zones with fixed offsets from UTC, such as UTC itself or North American EST and EDT time zones.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Supporting time zones at deeper levels of detail is up to the application.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The rules for time adjustment across the world are more political than rational, change frequently, and there is no standard suitable for every application aside from UTC.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The smallest year number allowed in a `date` or `datetime` object.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The largest year number allowed in a `date` or `datetime` object.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Alias for the UTC time zone singleton `datetime.timezone.utc`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] An idealized naive date, assuming the current Gregorian calendar always was, and always will be, in effect.
[src:python/datetime-p01] An idealized time, independent of any particular day, assuming that every day has exactly 24*60*60 seconds.
[src:python/datetime-p01] (There is no notion of “leap seconds” here.) Attributes: `hour`, `minute`, `second`, `microsecond`, and `tzinfo`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Attributes: `year`, `month`, `day`, `hour`, `minute`, `second`, `microsecond`, and `tzinfo`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] A duration expressing the difference between two `datetime` or `date` instances to microsecond resolution.
[src:python/datetime-p01] An abstract base class for time zone information objects.
[src:python/datetime-p01] These are used by the `datetime` and `time` classes to provide a customizable notion of time adjustment (for example, to account for time zone and/or daylight saving time).
[src:python/datetime-p01] A class that implements the `tzinfo` abstract base class as a fixed offset from the UTC.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Objects of the `date` type are always naive.
[src:python/datetime-p01] An object of type `time` or `datetime` may be aware or naive.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `t.tzinfo.utcoffset(None)` does not return `None`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The distinction between aware and naive doesn’t apply to `timedelta` objects.
[src:python/datetime-p01] A `timedelta` object represents a duration, the difference between two `datetime` or `date` instances.
[src:python/datetime-p01] All arguments are optional and default to 0.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Arguments may be integers or floats, and may be positive or negative.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Only *days*, *seconds* and *microseconds* are stored internally.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `import datetime as dt` instead of `import datetime` or `from datetime import datetime` to avoid confusion between the module and the class.
[src:python/datetime-p01] See How I Import Python’s datetime Module.
[src:python/datetime-p01] If any argument is a float and there are fractional microseconds, the fractional microseconds left over from all arguments are combined and their sum is rounded to the nearest microsecond using round-half-to-even tiebreaker.
[src:python/datetime-p01] If no argument is a float, the conversion and normalization processes are exact (no information is lost).
[src:python/datetime-p01] If the normalized value of days lies outside the indicated range, `OverflowError` is raised.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Note that normalization of negative values may be surprising at first.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The smallest possible difference between non-equal `timedelta` objects, `timedelta(microseconds=1)`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Note that, because of normalization, `timedelta.max` is greater than `-timedelta.min`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `-timedelta.max` is not representable as a `timedelta` object.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Division by zero raises `ZeroDivisionError`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] String representations of `timedelta` objects are normalized similarly to their internal representation.
[src:python/datetime-p01] This leads to somewhat unusual results for negative timedeltas.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The expression `t2 - t3` will always be equal to the expression `t2 + (-t3)` except when t3 is equal to `timedelta.max`; in that case the former will produce a result while the latter will overflow.
[src:python/datetime-p01] In addition to the operations listed above, `timedelta` objects support certain additions and subtractions with `date` and `datetime` objects (see below).
[src:python/datetime-p01] Changed in version 3.2: Floor division and true division of a `timedelta` object by another `timedelta` object are now supported, as are remainder operations and the `divmod()` function.
[src:python/datetime-p01] True division and multiplication of a `timedelta` object by a `float` object are now supported.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `timedelta` objects support equality and order comparisons.
[src:python/datetime-p01] In Boolean contexts, a `timedelta` object is considered to be true if and only if it isn’t equal to `timedelta(0)`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Return the total number of seconds contained in the duration.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Equivalent to `td / timedelta(seconds=1)`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] For interval units other than seconds, use the division form directly (for example, `td / timedelta(microseconds=1)`).
[src:python/datetime-p01] Note that for very large time intervals (greater than 270 years on most platforms) this method will lose microsecond accuracy.
[src:python/datetime-p01] A `date` object represents a date (year, month and day) in an idealized calendar, the current Gregorian calendar indefinitely extended in both directions.
[src:python/datetime-p01] If an argument outside those ranges is given, `ValueError` is raised.
[src:python/datetime-p01] This is equivalent to `date.fromtimestamp(time.time())`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Return the local date corresponding to the POSIX *timestamp*, such as is returned by `time.time()`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] This may raise `OverflowError`, if the timestamp is out of the range of values supported by the platform C `localtime()` function, and `OSError` on `localtime()` failure.
[src:python/datetime-p01] It’s common for this to be restricted to years from 1970 through 2038.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Note that on non-POSIX systems that include leap seconds in their notion of a timestamp, leap seconds are ignored by `fromtimestamp()`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Changed in version 3.3: Raise `OverflowError` instead of `ValueError` if the timestamp is out of the range of values supported by the platform C `localtime()` function.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Raise `OSError` instead of `ValueError` on `localtime()` failure.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Return the date corresponding to the proleptic Gregorian *ordinal*, where January 1 of year 1 has ordinal 1.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `ValueError` is raised unless `1 <= ordinal <= date.max.toordinal()`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] For any date `d`, `date.fromordinal(d.toordinal()) == d`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Extended date representations are not currently supported (`±YYYYYY-MM-DD`).
[src:python/datetime-p01] Ordinal dates are not currently supported (`YYYY-OOO`).
[src:python/datetime-p01] Changed in version 3.11: Previously, this method only supported the format `YYYY-MM-DD`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Return a `date` corresponding to the ISO calendar date specified by *year*, *week* and *day*.
[src:python/datetime-p01] This is the inverse of the function `date.isocalendar()`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Return a `date` corresponding to *date_string*, parsed according to *format*.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `ValueError` is raised if the date_string and format can’t be parsed by `time.strptime()` or if it returns a value which isn’t a time tuple.
[src:python/datetime-p01] See also strftime() and strptime() behavior and `date.fromisoformat()`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] If *format* specifies a day of month without a year a `DeprecationWarning` is emitted.
[src:python/datetime-p01] This is to avoid a quadrennial leap year bug in code seeking to parse only a month and day as the default year used in absence of one in the format is not a leap year.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Such *format* values may raise an error as of Python 3.15.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The workaround is to always include a year in your *format*.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The earliest representable date, `date(MINYEAR, 1, 1)`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The latest representable date, `date(MAXYEAR, 12, 31)`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] The smallest possible difference between non-equal date objects, `timedelta(days=1)`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Between `MINYEAR` and `MAXYEAR` inclusive.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Between 1 and the number of days in the given month of the given year.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `timedelta.seconds` and `timedelta.microseconds` are ignored.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `timedelta.seconds` and `timedelta.microseconds` are 0, and `date2 + timedelta == date1` after.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `date` objects are equal if they represent the same date.
[src:python/datetime-p01] `date` objects that are not also `datetime` instances are never equal to `datetime` objects, even if they represent the same date.
[src:python/datetime-p01] *date1* is considered less than *date2* when *date1* precedes *date2* in time.
[src:python/datetime-p01] In other words, `date1 < date2` if and only if `date1.toordinal() < date2.toordinal()`.
[src:python/datetime-p01] Order comparison between a `date` object that is not also a `datetime` instance and a `datetime` object raises `TypeError`.
