[src:python/datetime-p02] `ValueError` will be raised on an invalid *timespec* argument.
[src:python/datetime-p02] For a time `t`, `str(t)` is equivalent to `t.isoformat()`.
[src:python/datetime-p02] Return a string representing the time, controlled by an explicit format string.
[src:python/datetime-p02] See also strftime() and strptime() behavior and `time.isoformat()`.
[src:python/datetime-p02] This makes it possible to specify a format string for a `time` object in formatted string literals and when using `str.format()`.
[src:python/datetime-p02] If `tzinfo` is `None`, returns `None`, else returns `self.tzinfo.utcoffset(None)`, and raises an exception if the latter doesn’t return `None` or a `timedelta` object with magnitude less than one day.
[src:python/datetime-p02] If `tzinfo` is `None`, returns `None`, else returns `self.tzinfo.dst(None)`, and raises an exception if the latter doesn’t return `None`, or a `timedelta` object with magnitude less than one day.
[src:python/datetime-p02] If `tzinfo` is `None`, returns `None`, else returns `self.tzinfo.tzname(None)`, or raises an exception if the latter doesn’t return `None` or a string object.
[src:python/datetime-p03] This is an abstract base class, meaning that this class should not be instantiated directly.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Define a subclass of `tzinfo` to capture information about a particular time zone.
[src:python/datetime-p03] An instance of (a concrete subclass of) `tzinfo` can be passed to the constructors for `datetime` and `time` objects.
[src:python/datetime-p03] The latter objects view their attributes as being in local time, and the `tzinfo` object supports methods revealing offset of local time from UTC, the name of the time zone, and DST offset, all relative to a date or time object passed to them.
[src:python/datetime-p03] You need to derive a concrete subclass, and (at least) supply implementations of the standard `tzinfo` methods needed by the `datetime` methods you use.
[src:python/datetime-p03] The `datetime` module provides `timezone`, a simple concrete subclass of `tzinfo` which can represent time zones with fixed offset from UTC such as UTC itself or North American EST and EDT.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Special requirement for pickling: A `tzinfo` subclass must have an `__init__()` method that can be called with no arguments, otherwise it can be pickled but possibly not unpickled again.
[src:python/datetime-p03] This is a technical requirement that may be relaxed in the future.
[src:python/datetime-p03] A concrete subclass of `tzinfo` may need to implement the following methods.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Exactly which methods are needed depends on the uses made of aware `datetime` objects.
[src:python/datetime-p03] If in doubt, simply implement all of them.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Return offset of local time from UTC, as a `timedelta` object that is positive east of UTC.
[src:python/datetime-p03] If local time is west of UTC, this should be negative.
[src:python/datetime-p03] This represents the *total* offset from UTC; for example, if a `tzinfo` object represents both time zone and DST adjustments, `utcoffset()` should return their sum.
[src:python/datetime-p03] If the UTC offset isn’t known, return `None`.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Else the value returned must be a `timedelta` object strictly between `-timedelta(hours=24)` and `timedelta(hours=24)` (the magnitude of the offset must be less than one day).
[src:python/datetime-p03] If `utcoffset()` does not return `None`, `dst()` should not return `None` either.
[src:python/datetime-p03] The default implementation of `utcoffset()` raises `NotImplementedError`.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Return the daylight saving time (DST) adjustment, as a `timedelta` object or `None` if DST information isn’t known.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Return `timedelta(0)` if DST is not in effect.
[src:python/datetime-p03] If DST is in effect, return the offset as a `timedelta` object (see `utcoffset()` for details).
[src:python/datetime-p03] Note that DST offset, if applicable, has already been added to the UTC offset returned by `utcoffset()`, so there’s no need to consult `dst()` unless you’re interested in obtaining DST info separately.
[src:python/datetime-p03] For example, `datetime.timetuple()` calls its `tzinfo` attribute’s `dst()` method to determine how the `tm_isdst` flag should be set, and `tzinfo.fromutc()` calls `dst()` to account for DST changes when crossing time zones.
[src:python/datetime-p03] must return the same result for every `datetime` *dt* with `dt.tzinfo == tz`.
[src:python/datetime-p03] For sane `tzinfo` subclasses, this expression yields the time zone’s “standard offset”, which should not depend on the date or the time, but only on geographic location.
[src:python/datetime-p03] The implementation of `datetime.astimezone()` relies on this, but cannot detect violations; it’s the programmer’s responsibility to ensure it.
[src:python/datetime-p03] If a `tzinfo` subclass cannot guarantee this, it may be able to override the default implementation of `tzinfo.fromutc()` to work correctly with `astimezone()` regardless.
[src:python/datetime-p03] The default implementation of `dst()` raises `NotImplementedError`.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Return the time zone name corresponding to the `datetime` object *dt*, as a string.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Nothing about string names is defined by the `datetime` module, and there’s no requirement that it mean anything in particular.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Return `None` if a string name isn’t known.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Note that this is a method rather than a fixed string primarily because some `tzinfo` subclasses will wish to return different names depending on the specific value of *dt* passed, especially if the `tzinfo` class is accounting for daylight time.
[src:python/datetime-p03] The default implementation of `tzname()` raises `NotImplementedError`.
[src:python/datetime-p03] These methods are called by a `datetime` or `time` object, in response to their methods of the same names.
[src:python/datetime-p03] A `datetime` object passes itself as the argument, and a `time` object passes `None` as the argument.
[src:python/datetime-p03] A `tzinfo` subclass’s methods should therefore be prepared to accept a *dt* argument of `None`, or of class `datetime`.
[src:python/datetime-p03] When `None` is passed, it’s up to the class designer to decide the best response.
[src:python/datetime-p03] For example, returning `None` is appropriate if the class wishes to say that time objects don’t participate in the `tzinfo` protocols.
[src:python/datetime-p03] It may be more useful for `utcoffset(None)` to return the standard UTC offset, as there is no other convention for discovering the standard offset.
[src:python/datetime-p03] When a `datetime` object is passed in response to a `datetime` method, `dt.tzinfo` is the same object as *self*.
[src:python/datetime-p03] `tzinfo` methods can rely on this, unless user code calls `tzinfo` methods directly.
[src:python/datetime-p03] The intent is that the `tzinfo` methods interpret *dt* as being in local time, and not need worry about objects in other time zones.
[src:python/datetime-p03] This is called from the default `datetime.astimezone()` implementation.
[src:python/datetime-p03] When called from that, `dt.tzinfo` is *self*, and *dt*’s date and time data are to be viewed as expressing a UTC time.
[src:python/datetime-p03] The purpose of `fromutc()` is to adjust the date and time data, returning an equivalent datetime in *self*’s local time.
[src:python/datetime-p03] Most `tzinfo` subclasses should be able to inherit the default `fromutc()` implementation without problems.
